# {{ project_name }}

Built on **Terp** — secure-by-default by construction. The composition root is
`app/main.py`; the only editable surface is `app/modules/`.

## Setup

```bash
uv sync                               # backend deps (creates ./.venv)
npm --prefix frontend install         # frontend deps
uv run terp check                     # the architecture gate (== CI)
uv run terp dev                       # runs the API (:8000) + frontend (:5173) together
```

Backend commands run through `uv run …` — the `terp` CLI and the project's Python
live in the local `.venv`, not on the global PATH.

No starter module ships — sign-in, admin and audit are wired, and a fresh checkout is
gate-green as-is. `uv run terp new module <name>` (named after your actual domain) adds
the first module: model, migration, service, policy, router and a typed frontend view.

`uv run terp dev` refreshes the OpenAPI contract, then runs uvicorn (`--reload`) and the
Vite dev server side by side; stop either with Ctrl+C. Prefer them apart? `uv run uvicorn
app.main:app --reload` and `npm --prefix frontend run dev`. Without Docker the settings
default to an in-memory SQLite database — for data that survives a restart set
`DATABASE_URL=sqlite:///./dev.db` in `.env` and run `uv run terp migrate upgrade` once (the
Compose workbench below does all of this with Postgres instead).

## Run with Docker

For a prod-parity stack (Postgres, not SQLite) that seeds itself and live-reloads on edits:

```bash
cp .env.example .env      # optional: set a strong SECRET_KEY
uv run terp docker dev    # (or: docker compose watch)
```

This builds the images, brings up Postgres, runs the migrations, seeds a usable admin
(`admin@example.test`, password `correct horse battery staple`), then serves
the API (`:8000`) and the frontend (`:5173`) — editing `app/` or `frontend/src/` live-syncs
into the running containers. The one-off `app/seed.py` is where you put demo data worth
working against; production bootstraps its first admin with
`uv run terp user create <email> --role admin` instead (never `terp seed`).

## Add a module

```bash
uv run terp new module billing        # scaffolds the five slots (+ a frontend slot)
# mount it in app/main.py: import its `module`, add it to the modules list
uv run terp migrate make billing      # autogenerated migration
uv run terp check
```

See `AGENTS.md` and `uv run terp guide` for the authoring rules.

## Frontend

A React frontend is wired in `frontend/` (Vite + `@terpjs/react-core`), with one module
slot matching the backend. `frontend/src/modules/<name>/module.tsx` is auto-discovered —
no central registration, and `uv run terp new module <name>` adds the matching slot for you.

`uv run terp dev` runs it next to the API (see Setup). To type calls to your own endpoints,
generate the typed client from your backend and pass its `paths` to `useTerpClient`:

```bash
uv run terp openapi                 # write openapi.json from the live app
npm --prefix frontend run generate  # openapi.json -> frontend/src/api/schema.d.ts
```

```ts
import type { paths } from "../../api/schema";
const client = useTerpClient<paths>();   // now typed to YOUR endpoints
```

## Conformance

End-to-end browser flows run with [Playwright](https://playwright.dev) in `conformance/`, using the
base-profile helpers from `@terpjs/conformance` (sign-in gating, sign-out). Boot the workbench, then:

```bash
cd conformance
npm install
npx playwright install --with-deps chromium
npm test                              # drives the running stack (override with TERP_E2E_BASE_URL)
```

`conformance/tests/auth.spec.ts` covers the universal auth flow — add your own module specs
alongside it. CI runs the suite against the Docker workbench on every push.
